        args='{"prompt": "What are the useful life assumptions, depreciation methods, and property/equipment categories for each segment in {{spacex_s1}}? Include satellite useful lives, data center equipment lives, and any Starship-related asset lives.", "preserve_document_order": true}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What are the useful life assumptions, depreciation methods, and property/equipment categories for each segment in {{spacex_s1}}? Include satellite useful lives, data center equipment lives, and any Starship-related asset lives.',
            'preserve_document_order': True
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided financial disclosures, here is the detailed breakdown of the depreciation methods, property/equipment categories, and useful life assumptions across the Space, Connectivity, and AI segments.\n\n### 1. Depreciation Methods\n*   **Straight-Line Method:** The Company depreciates almost all Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E) using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets.\n*   **Flight-Based Method (Units of Production):** Flight vehicles and spacecraft are an exception; they are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** for each vehicle rather than a time-based schedule.\n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Refurbishments & Enhancements:** Routine maintenance is expensed as incurred. However, significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that extend an asset's life or functionality are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Property/Equipment Categories & Useful Life Schedule\nThe Company has established the following baseline useful lives for its PP&E categories:\n\n| Asset Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Servers and networking equipment** | 5 - 6 years |\n| **Satellites** | 3 - 5 years |\n| **Machinery and equipment** | 3 - 10 years |\n| **Flight vehicle hardware** | 5 - 25 flights |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | 20 - 25 years |\n| **Launch sites** | 7 - 20 years |\n| **Buildings and improvements** | 30 years |\n| **Leasehold improvements** | Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease |\n\n---\n\n### 3. Segment-Specific Assumptions & Critical Estimates\n\n#### **Space Segment (Launch Vehicles & Starship)**\n*   **Falcon 9 & Falcon Heavy Hardware:** Reusable components (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines) are classified as PP&E and depreciated to Cost of Revenue based on flight counts. Non-reusable second stages are treated as inventory and expensed upon launch.\n*   **Falcon 9 Booster Useful Life:** Although engineered and demonstrated to support up to 40 flights, the Company has established a **maximum accounting useful life of 25 flights**. This conservative estimate accounts for:\n    1.  The strategic transition to Starship (which will reduce future Falcon 9 demand).\n    2.  Government contract restrictions that prohibit the use of boosters flown more than 5 times on certain missions.\n*   **Starship (Development Stage):** Starship (boosters, ships, and Raptor engines) is currently in the development stage. Therefore, **it does not currently have a capitalized PP&E useful life or depreciation schedule**. A majority of Starship costs are expensed to *Research and Development* as incurred, and Raptor engines are expensed when used in test flights.\n*   **Dragon:** The fully reusable capsule is classified as PP&E and depreciated to Cost of Revenue based on expected flights.\n\n#### **Connectivity Segment (Satellites)**\n*   **Satellite Useful Lives:** Estimated at **3 to 5 years**. \n    *   *Broadband satellites:* **5-year** useful life.\n    *   *First-generation mobile satellites:* **3-year** useful life.\n*   **Estimation Factors:** Management determines these lives by evaluating on-orbit performance, propellant life, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, utilization patterns, and the evolution of constellation density/technology.\n*   **Sensitivity:** A one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would result in an approximately $480 million impact on annual operating income.\n\n#### **AI Segment (Compute & Data Centers)**\n*   **Servers & Networking Equipment:** Depreciated over **5 to 6 years**.\n*   **Data Center Infrastructure:** Depreciated over **20 to 25 years**.\n*   **Construction-in-Progress (CIP) & Capitalized Interest:** The AI segment is undergoing rapid terrestrial data center expansion. The Company capitalizes interest costs associated with these significant, long-term AI infrastructure construction projects until the assets are placed in service. \n\n---\n\n### 4. Impairment & Asset Retirement Policies\n*   **Impairment Triggers:** PP&E is evaluated for impairment at the lowest identifiable cash-flow level whenever events indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological obsolescence, damaged assets, or facility consolidations).\n*   **Recent Segment Impairments:** \n    *   *Space:* Write-offs of damaged flight vehicles.\n    *   *Connectivity:* Abandoned production lines and damaged satellite hardware.\n    *   *AI:* Leasehold improvements and office equipment written off due to facility consolidation/restructuring efforts.\n*   **Reassessment:** Useful lives and expected flight counts are periodically reassessed based on engineering data, post-flight inspections, recovery success rates, and the long-range launch manifest. If an asset's life is shortened or extended, the depreciation rate is adjusted prospectively.",
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=61.191,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
