2026-06-09 14:52:53,743 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## FY2025 Capex Intensity & Future Depreciation Expansion Analysis\n\n### Executive Conclusion\n\n**The AI segment is most likely to experience the most significant future depreciation expansion** — by a wide margin — based on its extreme capex intensity, the short useful lives of its primary assets, the massive pipeline of undepreciated capital, and explicit forward-looking statements about continued investment acceleration.\n\n---\n\n### 1. FY2025 Segment Capex Intensity Comparison\n\n| Metric | Space | Connectivity | AI | Consolidated |\n|:---|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| **FY2025 Revenue** | $4,086M | $11,387M | $3,201M | $18,674M |\n| **FY2025 Capex** | $3,832M | $4,178M | $12,727M | $20,737M |\n| **Capex Intensity (Capex/Revenue)** | **93.8%** | **36.7%** | **397.6%** | **111.1%** |\n| **FY2024 Capex Intensity** | 53.5% | 46.0% | 215.0% | 79.7% |\n| **YoY Intensity Change** | +40.3 pp | −9.3 pp | +182.6 pp | +31.4 pp |\n\nThe AI segment\'s capex is nearly **4× its revenue** — an extraordinary investment rate that dwarfs the other segments. Its capex intensity nearly doubled year-over-year (from 215% to 398%), while Connectivity\'s intensity actually *declined*, signaling relative maturity.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Depreciation Dynamics & the "Depreciation Pipeline"\n\n| Metric | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|:---|---:|---:|---:|\n| **FY2025 Depreciation** | $757M | $2,376M | $3,568M |\n| **FY2024 Depreciation** | $637M | $1,508M | $1,679M |\n| **YoY Depreciation Growth** | **18.8%** | **57.6%** | **112.5%** |\n| **Depreciation / Capex Ratio** | **19.8%** | **56.9%** | **28.0%** |\n| **Net Capital Formation (Capex − D&A)** | **$3,075M** | **$1,802M** | **$9,159M** |\n\n**The Depreciation/Capex ratio is the critical leading indicator.** It measures how much of current capex is already flowing through as depreciation:\n\n- **Connectivity (56.9%):** More than half of capex is already depreciating — the segment is in a steady-state reinvestment cycle. The satellite constellation is mature, and new satellite additions are partially offset by retirements of 3–5 year-life assets.\n- **Space (19.8%):** Low ratio reflects the surge in Starship-related capex, but much of Starship spending is **expensed as R&D** (not capitalized), limiting the depreciable base. Flight hardware is depreciated per-flight (units-of-production), not time-based, so depreciation expansion depends on launch cadence rather than asset age.\n- **AI (28.0%):** Only 28 cents of every dollar invested is currently depreciating. The remaining **$9.16 billion in net capital formation** represents a massive "depreciation pipeline" that will flow through the income statement as assets are placed in service.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Q1 2026 Depreciation Run-Rate Confirms Acceleration\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 D&A | Annualized Run-Rate | vs. FY2025 Full-Year |\n|:---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Space | $166M | $664M | −12.3%* |\n| Connectivity | $783M | $3,132M | +31.8% |\n| **AI** | **$1,493M** | **$5,972M** | **+67.4%** |\n\n*Space Q1 seasonality and per-flight depreciation timing make annualization less reliable.\n\nThe AI segment\'s Q1 2026 annualized depreciation run-rate of **$5.97B** represents a **67.4% increase** over FY2025\'s full-year $3.57B — confirming that the FY2025 capital additions are rapidly converting to depreciation charges.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Asset Composition Drives Depreciation Velocity\n\nThe PP&E categories most relevant to the AI segment have **short useful lives**, accelerating depreciation recognition:\n\n| Asset Category | Gross PP&E (FY2025) | Gross PP&E (FY2024) | YoY Change | Useful Life |\n|:---|---:|---:|---:|:---|\n| **Servers & networking** | $22,694M | $6,892M | **+$15,802M** | **5–6 years** |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | $2,960M | $224M | **+$2,736M** | **20–25 years** |\n| **Construction-in-progress** | $4,604M | $3,007M | **+$1,597M** | **Not yet depreciating** |\n\nThe **$15.8B surge in servers** is the dominant driver. At a 5.5-year midpoint useful life (straight-line), these assets will generate approximately **$2,873M/year** in depreciation once fully in service. The **$4.6B in CIP** (primarily AI data centers not yet placed in service) represents an additional depreciation pipeline that will begin flowing through as construction is completed.\n\n**Implied incremental annual depreciation from FY2025 net additions:**\n- Net capital formation of $9.16B at a blended 5.5-year life → **~$1,665M/year** in new depreciation\n- CIP conversion of $4.6B at a blended 5.5-year life → **~$837M/year** in new depreciation\n- **Total implied incremental depreciation: ~$2,500M/year** on top of the existing $3.57B base\n\n---\n\n### 5. Segment Economics Context\n\n| Metric (FY2025) | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|:---|---:|---:|---:|\n| **Segment Adj. EBITDA** | $653M | $7,168M | **$(1,237M)** |\n| **Adj. EBITDA Margin** | 16.0% | 62.9% | **(38.6%)** |\n| **D&A as % of Revenue** | 18.5% | 20.9% | **111.5%** |\n| **D&A as % of Adj. EBITDA** | 115.9% | 33.1% | **N/M (negative EBITDA)** |\n\nThe AI segment\'s depreciation ($3.57B) already **exceeds its revenue** ($3.20B) — a structural feature of its early-stage, capital-intensive buildout. The filing explicitly states the company expects a **"multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA."**\n\n---\n\n### 6. Required Assumptions to Support This Conclusion\n\nThe conclusion that the AI segment will experience the most significant future depreciation expansion rests on the following assumptions:\n\n| # | Assumption | Filing Support | Risk to Assumption |\n|:---|:---|:---|:---|\n| **1** | **Servers continue to be depreciated over 5–6 years (straight-line).** | Explicitly disclosed in accounting policies. | If useful lives are extended (as some hyperscalers have done), depreciation would be deferred but spread over a longer period. |\n| **2** | **CIP ($4.6B) converts to depreciable assets within 12–24 months.** | Filing states CIP is "primarily AI infrastructure" not yet in service; capitalized interest of $169M in FY2025 confirms active construction. | Construction delays, power procurement bottlenecks, or permitting issues could delay conversion. |\n| **3** | **Capex continues at or above FY2025 levels.** | Filing states capex will "scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute" and "continue to increase for the foreseeable future." | Capital markets tightening, power constraints, or strategic pivots could moderate spending. |\n| **4** | **No significant impairment or useful-life reassessment occurs.** | No AI-segment impairments recorded in FY2025 (only office leasehold write-offs from restructuring). | Rapid GPU obsolescence (e.g., next-gen chips rendering current hardware less competitive) could trigger impairment or accelerated depreciation. |\n| **5** | **The AI segment\'s revenue growth does not outpace depreciation growth sufficiently to achieve positive EBITDA in the near term.** | Filing explicitly discloses a "multi-year investment horizon" before sustained positive Adjusted EBITDA. | Breakthrough monetization (e.g., Grok enterprise adoption, API revenue scaling) could improve the revenue/depreciation ratio faster than expected. |\n| **6** | **IPO proceeds are deployed into AI infrastructure as disclosed.** | Filing states net proceeds earmarked for "expansion of AI compute infrastructure." | Alternative uses of proceeds (debt repayment, acquisitions) could reduce incremental capex. |\n\n---\n\n### 7. Why Not the Other Segments?\n\n**Space Segment:** While capex intensity surged to 93.8%, the depreciation expansion is structurally limited because:\n- Starship development costs are predominantly **R&D expensed**, not capitalized\n- Flight hardware uses **units-of-production depreciation** (per-flight), so depreciation scales with launch cadence, not time\n- Launch site infrastructure has longer useful lives (7–20 years), dampening annual depreciation impact\n- The transition to Starship may actually *reduce* Falcon 9 depreciation as the fleet is retired\n\n**Connectivity Segment:** Despite meaningful capex ($4.2B), depreciation expansion is moderated because:\n- Capex intensity is **declining** (46.0% → 36.7%), indicating the constellation is maturing\n- The 56.9% depreciation/capex ratio shows the segment is in a **steady-state replacement cycle**\n- Satellite retirements (3–5 year lives) partially offset new additions\n- A one-year change in satellite useful life would impact operating income by ~$480M, but this is a one-time adjustment, not a structural expansion\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe AI segment\'s **397.6% capex intensity**, **$9.16B net capital formation**, **28.0% depreciation/capex ratio** (lowest of all segments), **short asset lives (5–6 years)**, **$4.6B in undepreciated CIP**, and **explicit multi-year investment horizon** collectively make it the segment most likely to experience the most significant future depreciation expansion. The Q1 2026 data already confirms this trajectory, with AI depreciation running at a $5.97B annualized rate — 67% above FY2025 levels. Under the assumptions above, AI segment depreciation could reach **$6–7B annually by FY2026–2027**, fundamentally shaping the consolidated earnings trajectory.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (Filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
